/* History and contributors */ Deleted the people previously affiliated with CrossFit. None have been affiliated with CrossFit for several years and they have no relevance to the program or company as it currently exists.
/* Business model and CrossFit culture */
/* Business model and CrossFit culture */ Deleted the Jump rope course reference. It is irrelevant as it existed for a short period of time and has not existed as a CrossFit course for many years.
/* Business model and CrossFit culture */ updated the name of the Level 1 Trainer Course.
/* Business model and CrossFit culture */ Got rid of "though most adhere closely to the recommendations of CrossFit headquarters, or "HQ"" since it had no support citations.
/* Business model and CrossFit culture */ CrossFit Level 2 seminar no longer exists.
/* Programming and usage */
Updated the number of affiliates to 4,400
CrossFit existed as a fitness program prior to existing as a company. It's primarily a method. See: http://community.crossfit.com/video/crossfit-radio-episode-six-081026
/* History and contributors */ Removed the first sentence about starting the gym in Santa Cruz in 1995 due to lack of substantiation.
Added multi-level marketing to highlight Team Beachbody's innovative use of pyramid-style marketing to sell products, instead of selling them in stores.
Added Beachbody, one of the largest mult-level marketing corporations in the U.S.
/* New intro */
/* History */ added an "and" and deleted a comma.
/* History */ Deleted "former high-school gymnast" from before Greg Glassman. High school sporting history doesn't seem an appropriate way to introduce a CEO.
/* History */ There was no citation for Lauren Jenai having a part in founding CrossFit. The sources cited did not mention her name.

/* History */ Deleted [[Robb Wolf]], and Greg Everett from the list of "fitness experts" formerly associated with CrossFit. Everett is an olympic weightlifting coach and Robb Wolf focuses on nutrition.
/* History */ Deleted "weightlifting" from the Simmons, Starr, and Burgener sentence. Louie Simmons is a powerlifting coach, not a weightlifting coach.
Added citation for "constantly varied, high intensity, functional movements".
Added  “constantly varied, high intensity, functional movement" since this is how CrossFit defines its methods.

Deleted "They frequently move large loads quickly over long distances, and use [[powerlifting]] and [[Olympic weightlifting]] techniques." The first part is ambiguous in this context, and the second half of the sentence is redundant.
Deleted "kettlebell training" and "plyometric training". Kettlebell training is a relatively minor component of CrossFit, and plyometrics are rarely, if ever mentioned.
Added correct definition of fitness for CrossFit and gave citation.
Adding citation for "increased work capacity across broad time and modal domains"
Across all these domains -> across broad time and modal domains
/* History */ Added a citation for the number of CrossFit affiliates.
/* History */ Updated the number of affiliates. It said 1,700 in 2010. Now there are at least 3,400.
/* History */ Removed "Dr. Barry Sears, originator of the Zone diet." Sears is not a CrossFit subject matter expert.
/* CrossFit Games */
Updated the CrossFit Games prize from the $25,000 in 2010 to $250,000 in 2011.
Changed Scott DeWhore to the correct Scott DeTore. See: http://games2011.crossfit.com/finals/scoreboard/male/masters
Brian Curley was the male Masters champ in 2010, not Grant Nightengale. http://scores2010.crossfit.com/scoring/p/2010/masters-men,150/
